  saturated fat: 3 g
  carbohydrates: 58 g
  sugar: 12 g
  protein: 42 g
  fiber: 11 g
  sodium: 590 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/cajun-blackened-tilapia-lettuce-wraps-64ad64a508c61453c499a9c1
servings: 2
course: main course
cuisine: North America
author: Sara Heilman
---

Wash and dry produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(trimmed and sliced), separating whites from greens. Drain @black beans{1%can}. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}(zested and quartered). Trim and discard root end from @baby lettuce{1}; separate leaves.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites; cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly softened and fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in beans, @garlic powder{1%tsp}, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @water{1/4%cup}, and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low and cook until thickened, ~{7-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @tilapia{11%oz}(patted dry) dry with #paper towels{}; rub with @blackening spice{1%tbsp} and season with @salt{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{}, preferably nonstick, over medium heat. Add tilapia and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side. Transfer to a #cutting board{}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, half the @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%oz}, juice from half the lemon, and as much lemon zest as you like. Add @water{1%tsp} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Once beans are done, remove from heat; stir in juice from one lemon wedge. Cut tilapia into 12-16 pieces.

Divide lettuce leaves between plates; fill with tilapia and as many beans as you like. Sprinkle with scallion greens and drizzle with crema. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges and any remaining beans on the side.

> Tilapia is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.